annotatable.title: Whiskey Lullaby
annotatable.link_title: Whiskey Lullaby by Brad Paisley (Ft. Alison Krauss)

body.plain: “Whiskey Lullaby” is the title of a country song composed by Bill Anderson and Jon Randall. It was first recorded by Brad Paisley as a duet with Alison Krauss on Paisley’s 2003 album Mud on the Tires, and released on April 12, 2004, as that album’s third single, and the eleventh chart single of Paisley’s career. The song reached a peak of number three on the Billboard Hot Country Singles & Tracks (now Hot Country Songs) charts, and 41 on the Billboard Hot 100. The song won the 2005 Country Music Association Song of the Year award. It is one of Paisley’s three songs certified Platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America, the others being “She’s Everything” and “Then”.

annotatable.title: I'm Still A Guy
annotatable.link_title: I’m Still A Guy by Brad Paisley

body.plain:
Cowritten by Brad Paisley, Kelley Lovelace, and Lee Thomas Miller, “I’m Still A Guy” was released in March 2008 as the fourth single from Paisley’s album, 5th Gear (an auto reference)

The song is mid-tempo and set in triple meter. The lyrical contrast of masculine and feminine archetypes is intended, according to Paisley, to “capture this struggle a little bit between men and women in a playful way.”

More specifically, the song is a discussion of gender stereotypes.  Since it is essentially a celebration of hetero-normative notions of masculinity, it is very similar to some contemporary rap songs, like 50 Cent’s “In Da Club,” a so-called “brag track” detailing the performer’s “masculine” identity.

In Paisley’s case, the first-person narration articulates the differences between the singer and his romantic partner, who we can assume is a female because all of the indicators in the song seem to allow for exclusively heterosexual relationships.  The “you” of this song, therefore, is the narrator’s girlfriend or wife, for whom, by association with the narrator’s cliche masculinity, femininity is also caricatured.

One thing comes across clearly in Brad’s light-hearted play on these stereotypes: gender is always a performance.

A country song with similar stereotypical masculine themes was released by Tracy Byrd in 2003. He was joined by Blake Shelton, Andy Griggs and and Montgomery Gentry on * The Truth About Men *

annotatable.title: Love and War
annotatable.link_title: Love and War by Brad Paisley (Ft. John Fogerty)

body.plain:
This song touches on issues of war and veteran care/affairs, it follows the stories of a veteran who landed in Afghanistan (Bagram Airfield) at the age of 19, and a veteran who fought in the Vietnam War.

After coming home from the war both suffered from PTSD only to be neglected by the government.

body.plain:
“Country music is your grandpa’s music, but it’s also your daughter’s music, [and] it’s getting bigger and better all the time.” – Shania Twain

This is an anthem to the fans of country music. With shameless call-outs to a dozen U.S. universities, Paisley reminds us that there are more than a few educated folks who like country music.

body.plain: The song “Find Yourself” appears during the credits scene in the movie Cars and its about how Lightning Mcqueen’s (voiced by Owen Wilson) life changed  after coming to Radiator Springs. He was earlier a rookie racer trying to win a Piston Cup but now had turned into a person who realized there’s more to racing than just winning.

annotatable.link_title: Mud On The Tires by Brad Paisley

body.plain:
“Mud on the Tires” is the title track off Paisley’s third studio album. It was released in September 2004 as the album’s fourth and final single. The song reached number-one on the U.S. Billboard Hot Country Songs chart and peaked at number 30 on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100 chart. It was written by Paisley and Chris DuBois.

Lyrically, the song uses the repeated phrase “mud on the tires” as a analogy for a trysty romantic adventure.
